  "prompt": "What is the difference between a market maker, broker and a dealer?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the key differences between market makers, brokers, and dealers:\n\nMarket Makers:\n- Provide liquidity in financial markets\n- Buy and sell securities from their own inventory\n- Profit from the bid-ask spread\n- Guarantee continuous trading by always being willing to trade\n- Typically work for large financial institutions\n- Reduce market volatility and transaction costs\n\nBrokers:\n- Act as intermediaries between buyers and sellers\n- Do not own the securities they trade\n- Charge a commission or fee for executing trades\n- Help clients find the best prices\n- Do not take ownership of securities during transactions\n- Provide market advice and research\n\nDealers:\n- Buy and sell securities for their own account\n- Take ownership of securities\n- Profit from price differences when reselling\n- Can trade from their own inventory\n- Often specialize in specific types of securities\n- More actively manage their own trading positions\n\nKey differences:\n- Market makers always provide liquidity\n- Brokers facilitate trades for clients\n- Dealers trade for their own account\n- Market makers and dealers can hold securities, brokers cannot\n\nThese roles are crucial for maintaining efficient and liquid financial markets.",
